03605nam a22005415i 9780822372523DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20172017ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223725237 a10.1515/97808223725232doi  a(DE-B1597)552090  a(OCoLC)1048183640  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aTR102.S43 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a770.951/1322231 aSchaefer, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShadow Modernism :bPhotography, Writing, and Space in Shanghai, 1925-1937 /cWilliam Schaefer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b46 illustrations, incl. 8 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Picturing Photography, Abstracting Pictures -- t2. False Portals -- t3. Projected Pasts -- t4. Montage Landscapes -- t5. Shanghai Savage -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the early twentieth century, Shanghai was the center of China's new media culture. Described by the modernist writer Mu Shiying as "transplanted from Europe" and "paved with shadows," for many of its residents Shanghai was a city without a past paradoxically haunted by the absent past's traces. In Shadow Modernism William Schaefer traces how photographic practices in Shanghai provided a forum within which to debate culture, ethnicity, history, and the very nature of images. The central modernist form in China, photography was neither understood nor practiced as primarily a medium for realist representation; rather, photo layouts, shadow photography, and photomontage rearranged and recomposed time and space, cutting apart and stitching places, people, and periods together in novel and surreal ways. Analyzing unknown and overlooked photographs, photomontages, cartoons, paintings, and experimental fiction and poetry, Schaefer shows how artists and writers used such fragmentation and juxtaposition to make visible the shadows of modernity in Shanghai: the violence, the past, the ethnic and cultural multiplicity excluded and repressed by the prevailing cultural politics of the era and yet hidden in plain sight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aModernism (Art)zChinazShanghai. 0aPhotographyzChinazShanghaixHistoryy20th century. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822372523zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822372523.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles